{"slug": "diabolic", "root": "diabolic", "category": "quality", "gloss": "of the devil", "definition": "*Diabolic* means 'of the devil' — pertaining to Satan and his works, or to evil of a deliberate, malicious kind. In the history of magic it is the label that recast ordinary rites as demonic: a charm or cure becomes diabolic the moment authorities read a demon behind it.", "history": "From Greek *diabolos*, 'slanderer, accuser' (from *dia-*, 'across,' + *ballein*, 'to throw' — one who throws accusations), which named the Devil in Greek scripture; 'devil' is simply *diabolos* worn down. The Devil is, by his own title, the prosecutor. The word's decisive turn came in the later Middle Ages, when theologians and inquisitors folded folk magic, healing, and learned ritual into a single story of diabolical pact — the construction Michael Bailey traces of witchcraft as an accusation. To call an act diabolic was less to describe it than to convict it.", "def_sources": [{"label": "Bailey et al., The Sacred and the Sinister", "where": "Medieval magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Kieckhefer, Magic in the Middle Ages", "where": "Medieval magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Etymonline, s.v. diabolic (Greek diabolos)", "where": "Etymology reference"}], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"lang": "Greek", "origin": "Greek diabolos 'slanderer, accuser' (dia- 'across' + ballein 'to throw')", "first": "late 14c.", "note": "The Devil is, by his own name, 'the one who throws accusations'; 'devil' is just diabolos worn down.", "hook": "The Devil is, literally, the prosecutor."}, "essay": null, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_total": 1, "oracle_total": 0, "in_flavor_cards": 1, "in_oracle_cards": 0, "name_match_count": 11, "by_variant": {"diabolical": 1}, "first_year": 2009, "colors": {"B": 8, "R": 2, "C": 2, "G": 1, "U": 2}, "